          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  S]]></fr:tex> be a polarised abelian scheme of dimension <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g]]></fr:tex> over a smooth connected base <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
    For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s\in  S]]></fr:tex>, the fundamental group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _1(S,s)]]></fr:tex> acts on the fibre <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^1(X_s,\mathbb {Z})]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}_1f_*\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>.
    The polarisation of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> defines an alternating form on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^1(X_s,\mathbb {Z})]]></fr:tex>, with values in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}(-1)]]></fr:tex>, that is non-degenerate over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>, and the action of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _1(S,s)]]></fr:tex> respects this form.
    Consider the hypothesis:

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1699</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-4.4.14.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-4.4.14.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Hypothesis</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>4.4.14.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The morphism defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> to one of the irreducible components of the corresponding scheme of modules of polarised abelian varieties is a dominant morphism.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    <fr:p>The following result was suggested to me by J.-P. Serre.</fr:p></fr:p>
