          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> be a smooth connected scheme, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  S]]></fr:tex> a polarised abelian scheme over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> that satisfies <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.14.1" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.14.1.xml" taxon="Hypothesis" number="4.4.14.1" />.
    Then, for every abelian scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g\colon  Y\to  S]]></fr:tex>, we have
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {Hom}(X,Y)       \xrightarrow {\sim } \operatorname {Hom}(\mathrm {R}_1f_*\mathbb {Z},\mathrm {R}_1g_*\mathbb {Z}).     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1701</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#287</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-287.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s\in  S]]></fr:tex>.
      By <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.11" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.11.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="4.4.11" /> and <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.12" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.12.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="4.4.12" />, it suffices to show that the representation of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _1(S,s)]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\mathrm {R}_1f_*\mathbb {Q})_s]]></fr:tex> is absolutely irreducible, so that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H=\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>.
      This follows from the following lemma.</fr:p>
