          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> satisfies <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.14.1" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.14.1.xml" taxon="Hypothesis" number="4.4.14.1" />, then the image of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _1(S,s)]]></fr:tex> in the group of symplectic automorphisms of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^1(X_s,\mathbb {Z})]]></fr:tex> is of finite index.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1703</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#288</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-288.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> be an integer.
      Replacing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> by a surjective Ã©tale covering, defined by a finite-index subgroup of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _1(S,s)]]></fr:tex>, if necessary, we can assume that the local system <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{}_nX=\operatorname {Ker}(n\cdot \mathrm {Id}\colon  X\to  X)]]></fr:tex> is trivial on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
      Replacing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> by an isogenous abelian scheme, we can then assume that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is polarised in the principal series.
      Suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geqslant  3]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

    <fr:p>The abelian scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> then defines a dominant morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> from the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> to the scheme of "Jacobi" modules <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M_n]]></fr:tex> of polarised abelian schemes in the principal series endowed with a symplectic isomorphism between <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{}_nX]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\mathbb {Z}{/}n)^{2g}]]></fr:tex>;
      furthermore, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is an inverse image under <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> of the universal abelian scheme on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M_n]]></fr:tex>.
      
